        Hey I'm new here. Please don't take me seriously, I'm just a guy who loves music a lot & is a regular chart watcher who likes to give my thoughts on music of all kinds & what is charting. I am only doing this for fun.

        Anyway, here's some things I have to say about this particular chart week:
        Second week at Number 1 for We Don't Talk About Bruno. My thoughts on it being the first Disney song to reach number 1 in the UK? I'm alright with it. Maybe it's my love of Disney movies & also finally seeing Encanto recently (really enjoyed it, a lot better than I expected) but it's a catchy song with some amazing compositional moments & solid performances overall. Not my favourite Disney song ever (that honour goes to Under the Sea) but it is still pretty good. Much prefer to see this at number 1 than abcdefu.
        Easy on Me has now gone on ACR; Even though it had an impressive run & I do like the song a lot, I do feel kinda happy it's falling off now, cuz I don't wanna get sick of it & end up disliking it.
        Where Are You Now cracks the top 5! It's grown on me so much over the past couple of weeks; just an overall brilliant sounding track with a very good performance coming from Calum Scott. Happy it's gonna stick around, possibly become one of the biggest hits of 2022.
        The Family Madrigal, Make Me Feel Good & Down Under have all cracked the top 10! The Family Madrigal is a fun catchy number that opens & sets the scene for the movie very well. Make Me Feel Good isn't a stand out or original track at all, but it is still a solid house track with some nice keys. And as for Down Under, while I'm overall conflicted on what I think of Men At Work's iconic song getting a remake, I'm more interested in the fact that a drum & bass track has become this successful in 2022 & because of this, more drum & bass songs are charting; I'm just so happy this genre is gaining mainstream popularity again.
        Mr Brightside has now spend 300 weeks on the charts! I still don't understand how it's managed to build up as much momentum as it has, but it's always been a great song & a true noughties classic, so I don't care.
        Brave & Used to This are climbing! Really hope the latter gets in the top 40, one of the best dance songs I've heard in ages! It sounds so sweet, has a great atmosphere & is so groovy & well-produced; had it on repeat a lot lately & I'm happy it's Wilkinson's first charting song in years. I guess I could kind of credit Down Under for this. As for Brave, I just find it OK - pretty good lyrics but musically forgettable.
        Re-Entries for To the Moon, Don't Wake Me Up & Get Into It (Yuh). To the Moon has a great beat & is just an insanely fun catchy banger, Don't Wake Me Up is a forgettable bland slice of dance-pop/tropical house that I don't really have anything to say about (although it's at least better than the Chris Brown song of the same name) & Get Into It (Yuh)... is awful, I can't stand it at all, Jesus it's so bad.
        Do It To It is also finally on ACR & almost out of the Top 40 & unlike with Easy on Me, holy I'm so glad it is; it was one of my least favourite charting songs of last year, mainly because of it's poorly used sample & the atrocious production; I don't even like the original song that much, but it deserved better than this.
        Tell Me Something Good has completely fallen out of the Top 40; it was one of my favourite hits of 2021, a fantastically produced banger with some amazing musical elements & it does the original a tonne of justice; I'll even go as far as to say it's even better than the original & I hope Ewan doesn't end up a one hit wonder, cuz I've checked out his other songs & they are really good too, so I'm pretty devastated it fall hard! IMO, it really should have reached the top 10.
